<h1>
Running Test Programs
</h1>
<h2>
<a name=1></a>
Running on the Build Computer</h2>
<p>
There are no special steps required to run a test program
built with BullseyeCoverage on the local computer; run your program as normal.
Be sure the <code>COVFILE</code> environment variable names your coverage file.
<h2>
<a name=2></a>
Running on Multiple Computers</h2>
<p>
There are two ways to collect and merge coverage data on multiple computers.
<ol>
<li>
Share one coverage file on a network by setting environment variable
<code>COVFILE</code> on the remote computer to the network path of the
coverage file.
This alternative is simpler but requires adequate network performance.
<li>
Copy the coverage file to each remote computer and set
<code>COVFILE</code> on the remote computer to the path of the copy.
After testing is complete, merge the coverage files into one file for reporting.
Before making code changes or rebuilding, merge all copies of the coverage files back into the one on the build system.
To merge coverage files using the
<a href=coverageBrowser.html>Coverage Browser</a>,
use command
<code>File Insert</code>.
To merge coverage files at the command prompt, use
<a href=ref_covmerge.html>covmerge</a>.
</ol>
<h2>
<a name=3></a>
Collecting Data to Multiple Coverage Files</h2>
<p>
If you have multiple, separate projects which run together on the
same computer and each project has its own associated coverage file,
you can collect coverage data for all the projects simultaneously
without merging the coverage files.
Set environment variable <code>COVFILELIST</code>
to a comma separated list of the coverage file paths.
For example,
<pre>
COVFILELIST=/path1/test1.cov,/path2/test2.cov,/path3/test3.cov
</pre>
<p>
Environment variable <code>COVFILELIST</code> overrides <code>COVFILE</code>,
and is only used at run-time.
<h2>
<a name=4></a>
Controlling Run-Time Error Display</h2>
<p>
If an error occurs at run-time, BullseyeCoverage displays an error message to
the screen.
However, if environment variable
<a href=ref_environment.html#COVERR>COVERR</a>
is set to the name
of a file, BullseyeCoverage appends the message to the file instead.

